## File 1: /tmp/sv-d5f914391ab448d58ac5bf19f9cf9a0f/before/Extensions/ArmClientBuilderExtensions.cs

Line 30 calls `builder.RegisterClientFactory<ArmClient, ArmClientOptions>(configuration)` which is marked `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]`. Since this is calling an external method that fundamentally requires dynamic code, add `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]` to the `AddArmClient` method on line 27.

Add these attributes to the method:
```
[RequiresUnreferencedCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values is not supported with trimming.")]
[RequiresDynamicCode("Binding strongly typed objects to configuration values requires generating dynamic code at runtime.")]
```

Add `using System.Diagnostics.CodeAnalysis;` if not already present.

## File 2: /tmp/sv-d5f914391ab448d58ac5bf19f9cf9a0f/before/ArmEnvironment.cs

Line 80: `public override string ToString() => JsonSerializer.Serialize(this);`

`ArmEnvironment` is a struct. Replace with manual JSON serialization using Utf8JsonWriter. The struct has properties `Endpoint` (Uri) and `Audience` (string). Write it as:
```csharp
public override string ToString()
{
    using var stream = new System.IO.MemoryStream();
    using (var writer = new Utf8JsonWriter(stream))
    {
        writer.WriteStartObject();
        writer.WriteString("Endpoint", Endpoint.ToString());
        writer.WriteString("Audience", Audience);
        writer.WriteEndObject();
    }
    return System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(stream.ToArray());
}
```

## File 3: /tmp/sv-d5f914391ab448d58ac5bf19f9cf9a0f/before/ArmClientOptions.cs

Line 52: `var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>>(span);`

Replace with the `JsonSerializer.Deserialize` overload that takes a `JsonTypeInfo`. Use `JsonSerializerOptions.Default` to get the type info:
```csharp
var allProfile = JsonSerializer.Deserialize(span, ArmClientOptionsSerializerContext.Default.DictionaryStringDictionaryStringJsonElement);
```

Then create a source-generated context. Add at the bottom of the namespace (before the closing `}` of the namespace) in the same file:

```csharp
[JsonSerializerContext]
[JsonSerializable(typeof(Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, JsonElement>>))]
internal partial class ArmClientOptionsSerializerContext : JsonSerializerContext { }
```

Make sure `using System.Text.Json.Serialization;` is present.

## Files 4-7: LRO files that use `.ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>()`

These 4 files each have a line like:
```
var lroDetails = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default).ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>();
```

Replace `.ToObjectFromJson<Dictionary<string, string>>()` with using `JsonSerializer.Deserialize` with a typed context instead. Since `ToObjectFromJson` deserializes JSON from BinaryData, we need to use a source-generated approach.

Actually, the simplest fix is to parse the BinaryData as a JsonDocument and extract the "id" directly, since that's all that's used from the dictionary. Replace the entire `GetOperationId` method body with:

```csharp
if (rehydrationToken is null)
{
    return null;
}
var data = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default);
using var document = JsonDocument.Parse(data);
return document.RootElement.GetProperty("id").GetString();
```

